<p />
<h1><a name="About_this_Document"></a> About this Document </h1>
This document is for System Administrators. It explains best practices on how to upgrade from OSG 1.2, Pacman based releases, to OSG 3.0, based on RPMs.
<p />
<h1><a name="Differences_between_OSG_3_RPMs_a"></a> Differences between OSG 3 RPMs and OSG 1.2 Pacman installations </h1>
Here we are listing some differences in RPM installations that you should pay attention to if you are used to Pacman installations: <ul>
<li> While Pacman installation are self contained (all files reside within the tree rooted in the installation directory), RPM installations spread files within the system path using FHS conventions. This means: <ul>
<li> You must always be <code>root</code> to install OSG 3 software
</li> <li> Pacman installation are just using space until you source the setup file, RPM installations affect the system right away: <ul>
<li> binaries are in the PATH
</li> <li> libraries may replace or upgrade installed ones and be used by other programs
</li> <li> the installation may create users or modify files
</li> <li> uninstalling the packages is more tricky
</li> <li> it is not possible to install multiple versions at the same time
</li></ul> 
</li> <li> Pacman installations could be easily shared by exporting the install directory. This is not possible for OSG 3 RPMs because files are sparse in different places in the file system.
</li></ul> 
</li> <li> Read <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/YumRpmBasics" class="twikiLink">YumRpmBasics</a>, <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/YumRepositories" class="twikiLink">YumRepositories</a> and <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/InstallBestPractices" class="twikiLink">InstallBestPractices</a> if you are not familiar with RPMs and Yum repositories.
</li></ul> 
<p />
<p />
